title: 4.  Two Pairs of Major Vessels Supply the Brain

vectorData.altText: 19.1   Two Pairs of Major Vessels Supply the Brain

Branches of the internal carotid arteries (ICAs) supply antero-superior portions of the cerebrum and the anterior diencephalon.
The vertebral arteries (VAs) and their branches supply the brainstem & cerebellum, the posteroinferior portions of the cerebrum and the posterior diencephalon
How do these vessels gain access to the interior of the cranium?
The ICAs traverse the carotid canal     .
The VAs enter via the foramen magnum     .
The ICAs Traverse the Carotid Canal

the ICAs approach the skull base and enter the carotid canals
they traverse the carotid canals, taking a anteromedial course
they enter the cranial cavity on either side of the dorsum sellae AT the “foramen” lacerum
they form a carotid siphon within the cavernous sinus
they bifurcate (not shown) forming an anterior cerebral artery (ACA) and a middle cerebral artery (MCA)
From Grant’s Atlas of Anatomy, 11th ed., edited by Anne Agur, © 2005 by LWW

Remember: this is NOT a foramen in life, only in a dried skull. In life it is covered over by cartilage. It’s value to us is as a landmark indicating the point at which the ICAs enter the cranial cavity.
From Fundamental Neuroscience for Basic and Clinical Applications, 3rd ed., by Duane E. Haines, © 2006 by Elsevier.

The vertebral arteries (VA) branch from the subclavian artery in the root of the neck. 
They enter the cranium through the foramen magnum. 
They unite forming the basilar artery on the ventral aspect of the pons.
The Vertebral Arteries Enter via the Foramen Magnum
